                            <comment id="14454063" author="bentmann" created="Tue, 22 Jan 2008 05:17:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Besides the mentioned effects on the Surefire report, a lengthy test suite (say 5 - 6 minutes) will not show any progress feedback on the console while running all the aggregated test classes. Furthermore, all test output ends up in a single big file which is not real fun if one needs to analyze the output.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Attached is an integration test that passes with Surefire 2.3.1 but fails with Surefire 2.4.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454214" author="dfabulich" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 00:59:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In fact, the same thing happens when you create a JUnit TestSuite that includes tests from other classes: Maven generates just one XML file for the entire TestSuite.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Testing in Ant 1.7, I see that Ant does the same thing, too.  However, Ant includes a &quot;classname&quot; attribute on every testcase, which the report can use to guess what suite you&apos;re in.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The fix for this is to include the classname attribute on the generated XML and to honor it in the report plugin.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454187" author="bentmann" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 11:22:04 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;the same thing happens when you create a JUnit TestSuite that includes tests from other classes: Maven generates just one XML file for the entire TestSuite.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Attached is another integration test using JUnit, similar to the one currently failing for TestNG. The test asserts that the suite produces distinct output files (*.xml; *.txt) for each test class and it passes. So I wonder whether we are talking about the same use-case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454081" author="ahoehma" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 12:03:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;i confirm this bug.&lt;br/&gt;
perhaps this is a bug in a new version of testng?&lt;br/&gt;
i use testng 5.7 with surefire 2.4-SNAPSHOT&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;testng-results.xml (written by testng):&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;testng-results&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
  &amp;lt;reporter-output&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
  &amp;lt;/reporter-output&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
  &amp;lt;suite name=&quot;Command line suite&quot;&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;but then i have a&lt;br/&gt;
TestSuite.txt&lt;br/&gt;
TEST-TestSuite.xml&lt;br/&gt;
in the reports-directory&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454144" author="dfabulich" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 16:19:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Benjamin: it passes because you&apos;re using a JUnit directory suite.  If you&apos;d created a TestSuite object and included only that TestSuite object, it would have failed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve made a longer post about this on surefire-dev, but its archives are moderated, so you can look at the other copy I posted to the TestNG users list:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://groups.google.com/group/testng-users/browse_thread/thread/2d374aff62b5110b#a14ffcb7f30debe7&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://groups.google.com/group/testng-users/browse_thread/thread/2d374aff62b5110b#a14ffcb7f30debe7&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454127" author="bentmann" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 16:36:43 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;it passes because you&apos;re using a JUnit directory suite&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yeah, by intention &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; That&apos;s what this issue is all about, I mean using a (automatic generated) directory suite, isn&apos;t it? We have a couple of test classes somewhere in &lt;tt&gt;src/test/java&lt;/tt&gt; and want them to get run individually with the TestNG provider just like the JUnit provider would do. If we wanted an all aggregating suite, we could have setup our own hand-crafted suite but aggregating test classes is not helpful/desired here.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454064" author="dfabulich" created="Thu, 24 Jan 2008 19:40:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Benjamin: My point in the long post was that Surefire sometimes puts all of the test results into one file, but so does TestNG itself!  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&apos;s supposed to be fine; TestNG can/should be allowed to do that, and we should be able to report on it correctly.  surefire-report should be able to read that file and separate the tests out into their individual classes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14454194" author="dfabulich" created="Fri, 25 Jan 2008 14:16:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK, I think this is &quot;fixed&quot; the way I thought I&apos;d fix it in r61526.  This may not be the &quot;right&quot; way to fix it, but I think it is.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17993770" author="olamy" created="Fri, 4 Jul 2025 07:09:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This project has moved from Jira to GitHub Issues. This issue was migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/maven-surefire/issues/1271&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;apache/maven-surefire#1271&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
